<subsection>
  <title>A Big Disclaimer</title>

  <p>
    A lot of our statistical techniques and analysis is predicated on the Central Limit Theorem.  It's an extremely powerful tool to use sample size to force normality and reduce variability.  But the Central Limit Theorem <em>Only applies to random variables with a defined mean and standard deviation.</em>  This does not describe every possible random variable.
  </p>
  
  <p>  Suppose you had an archer with a magic bow.  She picks an angle between 0 and <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians, and fires.  The height the arrow reaches after to travels forward for 1 foot is a random variable.  More importantly, it has no mean or variance!  This means that as we increase the sample size of random samples on this variable, there is no discernable pattern.  Desmos doesn't have the firepower to do it true justice but you can get an idea:
  <interactive desmos="inpq2hsref"/>
  Even sample sizes up to <m>n=1000</m> don't cause the mean or standard deviation to converge!
  </p>  

  <p>
    What this means is that the Central Limit Theorem won't apply to any old random variable you find lying around.  But when you collect data, it's rarely clear if the data you collect from is something with defined mean and deviation or not.  These sort of distributions often seem well behaved but are subject to high volativity that only reveals itself upon large number of data points, as seen above.  These are often dismissed as outliers!
  </p>
  
  <p>
  The bottom line is to be careful when using statistical techniques, there are dark and deep waters out here.
  </p>  












</subsection>

